<subSubSection id="96BC651BB72F285D08F2F68C3A1BF663" pageId="10" pageNumber="400" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="DE193690B72F285D08F2F68C3A1BF663" blockId="10.[166,1374,878,2681]" pageId="10" pageNumber="400">
<emphasis id="ECD2EA82B72F285D08F2F68C3D5FF686" bold="true" box="[168,513,2333,2366]" pageId="10" pageNumber="400">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
CITES Appendix II. Classified as Least Concern on The [UCN Red List (as 
<taxonomicName id="19A64D13B72F285D090BF6D53EC6F6DD" authorityName="Erxleben" authorityYear="1777" box="[337,408,2372,2405]" class="Mammalia" family="Cebidae" genus="Cebus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="10" pageNumber="400" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Cebus</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName id="19A64D13B72F285D09F9F6D53E8EF6DD" authorityName="Illiger" authorityYear="1815" box="[419,464,2372,2405]" class="Mammalia" family="Cebidae" genus="Sapajus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="10" pageNumber="400" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cay">cay</taxonomicName>
). The Hooded Capuchin is widespread but poorly known. It occurs in Barita, Calilegua, and El Rey national parks in Argentina, Noel Kempff Mercado National Park in Bolivia, Pantanal Matogrossense and Serra da Bodoquena national parks in Brazil, and Caaguazu, Cerro Cora, and Ybycui national parks in Paraguay.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
